defs.def: to (cause to) stop suddenly and remain motionless:
examples: [no object]I froze when I heard the sound.
[~ + object]The snap of a twig behind him froze him in his tracks.

defs.def: to (cause to) become blocked or obstructed by the formation of ice:
examples: [no object]The water pipes froze.
[~ + object]The cold froze the pipes.
[no object] to work or function badly because of cold: [no object]The engine froze during the night and wouldn't start.

defs.def: to (cause to) become fixed or stuck to something by or as if by the action of frost:
examples: [no object]The sled froze to the sidewalk.
[~ + object]The wiper was frozen to the windshield.

defs.def: to become unfriendly or secretive:
examples: [no object;  ~ (+ up)]She froze up when we questioned her.

defs.def: to fix (rents, prices, etc.) at a specific amount, usually by government order:
examples: [~ + object]Why is it that wages are frozen while prices rise?

defs.def: to stop or limit production or use of:
examples: [~ + object]an agreement to freeze nuclear weapons.

defs.def: to prevent (assets) from being sold or collected:
examples: [~ + object]The government froze their accounts.
The highway froze over.

defs.def: an act or instance of freezing;
a period of very cold weather:
examples: A freeze set in.

defs.def: a legislative action to control prices, rents, production, etc.:
examples: imposed a wage freeze.

defs.def: a decision by one or more nations to stop or limit production or development of weapons:
examples: calling for a freeze on nuclear weapons.

defs.def: to become hardened into ice or into a solid body;
to become hard or stiffened because of loss of heat, as objects containing moisture:
examples: Meat will freeze in a few hours.

defs.def: to suffer the effects of intense cold;
examples: We sat there freezing until the heat came on.

defs.def: to be of the degree of cold at which water freezes:
examples: It may freeze tonight.

defs.def: to lose warmth of feeling;
examples: My heart froze when she told me the news.

defs.def: to become immobilized through fear, shock, etc.:
examples: When he got in front of the audience he froze.

defs.def: to stop suddenly and remain motionless;
examples: I froze in my tracks.

defs.def: to become obstructed by the formation of ice, as pipes:
examples: Our basement water pipes often freeze in winter.

defs.def: to die or be injured because of frost or cold.
(of a screw, nail, or the like) to become rigidly fixed in place, as from rust or dirt.
to become fixed to something by or as if by the action of frost.
to become unfriendly, secretive, or aloof (often fol. by
examples: He froze at such a personal question.

defs.def: to become temporarily inoperable;
examples: The new software made my computer freeze.

defs.def: to harden into ice;
to form ice on the surface of (a river, pond, etc.).
to harden or stiffen (an object containing moisture) by cold.
to quick-freeze.
to subject to freezing temperature;
to cause to suffer the effects of intense cold;
to cause to lose warmth as if by cold;
to cause (a person or animal) to become fixed through fright, alarm, shock, etc.:
examples: Terror froze him to the steering wheel.

defs.def: to kill by frost or cold:
examples: A late snow froze the buds.

defs.def: to fix fast with ice:
examples: a sled frozen to a sidewalk.

defs.def: to obstruct or close (a pipe or the like) by the formation of ice:
examples: The storm had frozen the hydrant.

defs.def: to fix (rents, prices, etc.) at a specific amount, usually by government order.
to stop or limit production, use, or development of:
examples: an agreement to freeze nuclear weapons.

defs.def: to render impossible of liquidation or collection:
examples: Bank loans are frozen in business depressions.

defs.def: to render part of the body insensitive to pain or slower in its function by artificial means.
to photograph (a moving subject) at a shutter speed fast enough to produce an unblurred, seemingly motionless image.
to stop by means of a freeze-frame mechanism:
examples: You can freeze the action at any point.

defs.def: to maintain possession of (a ball or puck) for as long as possible, usually without trying to score, thereby reducing the opponent's opportunities for scoring.
to hold (a puck) against the boards with the skates or stick, causing play to stop and forcing a face-off.
or
to exclude or compel (somebody) to withdraw from membership, acceptance, a position of influence or advantage, etc., by cold treatment or severe competition.
to coat or become coated with ice:
examples: The lake freezes over for several months each year.

defs.def: the act of freezing;
Also called
examples: A freeze is expected in the coastal areas.

defs.def: a frost.
a legislative action, esp. in time of national emergency, to control prices, rents, production, etc.:
examples: The government put a freeze on new construction.

defs.def: a decision by one or more nations to stop or limit production or development of weapons, esp. nuclear weapons.
